<%#
  Multi-language drill mock (#multilang).
  Static states laid out top-to-bottom so the whole interaction reads at a glance.
  No JS, no live grading — every value is hard-coded stub data.
  Concept used throughout: source EN "bread" → nl brood / es pan / fr pain.
%>

<div class="space-y-16">

  <%# =====================================================================
      SECTION 1 — choosing which languages you drill
      Evolves the existing two single-selects into: one source + a chip
      multi-select of targets. The 5 dormant languages just become selectable.
  ====================================================================== %>
  <section>
    <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">1 · Pick your languages</h2>
    <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-gray-400 dark:text-gray-500">Settings / onboarding. One you speak, any number you're learning.</p>

    <div class="mt-4 max-w-md space-y-5">
      <div>
        <label class="block text-xs font-medium text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">I already speak</label>
        <div class="mt-1.5 inline-flex rounded-lg border border-gray-300 bg-gray-50 p-0.5 dark:border-gray-700 dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="rounded-md bg-white px-3 py-1.5 text-sm shadow-sm dark:bg-gray-700">English</span>
          <span class="px-3 py-1.5 text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Dutch</span>
          <span class="px-3 py-1.5 text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Russian</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <label class="block text-xs font-medium text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">I'm learning</label>
        <p class="mt-0.5 text-[11px] text-gray-400 dark:text-gray-500">Tap to add. Drill any of these — together or one at a time.</p>
        <div class="mt-2 flex flex-wrap gap-2">
          <% selected = %w[Dutch Spanish French] %>
          <% all = %w[Dutch Spanish French Italian Romanian Russian] %>
          <% all.each do |lang| %>
            <% if selected.include?(lang) %>
              <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 rounded-full border border-gray-900 bg-gray-900 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-white dark:border-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-100 dark:text-gray-900">
                <%= lang %> <span class="text-gray-400 dark:text-gray-500">×</span>
              </span>
            <% else %>
              <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full border border-gray-300 px-3 py-1 text-xs text-gray-500 dark:border-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400">
                <%= lang %>
              </span>
            <% end %>
          <% end %>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# =====================================================================
      SECTION 2 — choosing how many to drill at once, at the deck/start screen
      Resting state shows the current value; the option set is a quiet segmented
      control right where you start a drill. Default = all your learning langs.
  ====================================================================== %>
  <section>
    <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">2 · Start a drill</h2>
    <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-gray-400 dark:text-gray-500">On the deck / home screen, next to the deck you pick.</p>

    <div class="mt-4 max-w-md rounded-lg border border-gray-200 px-4 py-3 dark:border-gray-800">
      <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between">
        <span class="text-sm font-medium">Kitchen &amp; food</span>
        <span class="text-[11px] tabular-nums text-gray-400">42 words</span>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-3 flex items-center gap-2 text-xs">
        <span class="text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Drill</span>
        <span class="inline-flex rounded-lg border border-gray-300 bg-gray-50 p-0.5 dark:border-gray-700 dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="px-2.5 py-1 text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Dutch only</span>
          <span class="rounded-md bg-white px-2.5 py-1 shadow-sm dark:bg-gray-700">all 3 at once</span>
        </span>
        <span class="text-gray-400 dark:text-gray-500">→</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 max-w-md text-[11px] text-gray-400 dark:text-gray-500">"All 3" = the concept card below: one English prompt, you supply Dutch, Spanish, French in turn.</p>
  </section>

  <%# =====================================================================
      SECTION 3 — THE CORE INTERACTION: the concept card, sequential reveal
      One concept pinned at the top; one input live at a time; prior answers
      lock in above as a quiet completed band. Three frozen frames of the SAME
      card so the motion reads without JS.
  ====================================================================== %>
  <section>
    <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">3 · The concept card — drilling 3 languages of one word</h2>
    <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-gray-400 dark:text-gray-500">Same card, three moments. One input live at a time; answered languages settle above it.</p>

    <div class="mt-5 grid gap-5 sm:grid-cols-3">

      <%# ---- Frame A: first language, nothing answered yet ---- %>
      <%= render "mocks/mld_card",
            step_label: "1 of 3",
            done: [],
            current: { name: "Dutch", placeholder: "dutch…" },
            input_value: nil, input_state: :empty,
            upcoming: %w[Spanish French],
            caption: "Fresh card. First target asked." %>

      <%# ---- Frame B: Dutch answered correct, Spanish now live ---- %>
      <%= render "mocks/mld_card",
            step_label: "2 of 3",
            done: [{ name: "Dutch", answer: "brood", ok: true }],
            current: { name: "Spanish", placeholder: "spanish…" },
            input_value: "pan", input_state: :ready,
            upcoming: %w[French],
            caption: "Dutch locked in above. Spanish typed, ready to check." %>

      <%# ---- Frame C: all three answered, one missed ---- %>
      <%= render "mocks/mld_card",
            step_label: "done",
            done: [
              { name: "Dutch",   answer: "brood", ok: true },
              { name: "Spanish", answer: "pan",   ok: true },
              { name: "French",  answer: "pian",  ok: false, correct: "pain" },
            ],
            current: nil,
            input_value: nil, input_state: :done,
            upcoming: [],
            caption: "Card complete. The miss shows its correction; 2/3 right." %>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# =====================================================================
      SECTION 4 — why sequential reveal, not all-fields-at-once
      A short honest note on the alternative considered, so the decision is legible.
  ====================================================================== %>
  <section class="max-w-2xl">
    <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Note · why one input at a time</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1.5 text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">
      <li>· Keeps the single-input flashcard rhythm the app already nails — type, check, next — instead of turning a card into a 3-field form.</li>
      <li>· Each language is its own graded attempt (records exactly like today: one row per from→to pair). No tracking changes.</li>
      <li>· The concept stays whole: you watch "bread" assemble across languages on one card — that's the value Anki only does by hand.</li>
      <li>· A blank field is never ambiguous (skip? don't know?) — there's only ever one field to fill.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</div>
